What’s this all about?…

  • Broadly speaking, the objective of statistical analysis is to produce “some summary” of the available data
  • Sometimes, it is at least theoretically possible to deal with an entire population of observable quantities (e.g. census). In this case, every unit is measured and we can produce some descriptive statistics
    • Mean height of population
    • Standard deviation of age



  • However, in most cases measuring a whole population is impossible or extremely difficult
    • Economic reasons: to measure many units might be very expensive
    • Accuracy reasons: sometimes it is better to measure very precisely just some units instead of measuring very imprecisely many units
    • Physical reasons: sometimes the very measurement destroys the unit (e.g. time to death)


  • Therefore we need to rely on a subset of individuals (units) for which a measurement is indeed available, and make inference about the unobservable overall population

EXAMPLE: Which country has the highest child mortality rates?

For each of the five pairs of countries below, which do you think has the highest child mortality rates in 2015?

  1. Sri Lanka or Turkey?
  2. Poland or South Korea?
  3. Malaysia or Russia?
  4. Pakistan or Vietnam?
  5. Thailand or South Africa?



Intuition: “Western” countries are characterised by long life span and small families, while the “developing” world has short life span and large families. BUT: do they?…


The late Swedish epidemiologist Hans Rosling (the founder of Gapminder) used this question in one of his videos (“New insights on poverty” — https://tinyurl.com/yxk79qms)

Let’s take stock for a moment…



Technical comments

  • Trends can be tricky to spot — we may think that a linear decrease is reasonable, but probably, once we tried, we’d be happier with a smoother, non-linear trend
    • Basically, we do not know — so it’s a good thing to test various assumptions!
  • It’s a good idea to show the same data under different perspectives
    • For instance, with and without grouping by continent to see if we can gain some more insight into the features of the data generating process


Substantive comments

  • The analysis of the historical data (from 1962, in this case) seems to confirm the intuition that, indeed, “western” countries (eg in Europe and North America) do have smaller families and longer life expectancy
  • And indeed “developing” countries (eg in Africa, Asia and Latin America) tend to have shorter life expectancy with larger families
  • So there must be something that over time has modified these patterns…
  • Can we explore further?

The importance of “binning”

Data transformations & summaries

  • This graph shows that the empirical sampling distribution of the data is highly skewed
    • A large number of units is highly concentrated on small values of the outcome, but there are also many units who have a single, larger value
    • This is interesting because this descriptive analysis can be used to inform our modelling — a Normal distribution (eg a linear model) is certainly not a great idea!



  • It may be a good idea to rescale/transform the data to make more sense of them
    • Can think in terms of progression of income:
      1. $1 = extremely poor
      2. $2 = very poor
      3. $4 = poor
      4. $8 = middle
      5. $16 = well off
      6. $32 = rich
      7. $64 = very rich
    • This naturally links to logarithms (in base 2)


  • In any case, a histogram is still a representation of the data based on assumptions (eg binning) — not the “truth” (if such thing could ever exist…)

Data transformations & summaries

Data transformations & summaries

Graphs are a good way to summarise the data, but often we want to have some numerical summary to convey the information

Measures of Location (or level)

\[\displaystyle\textsf{Arithmetic mean: }\color{blue}{\mu = \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{y_i}{N}}\]

\[\textsf{Median: } \color{blue}{\textsf{Med}(Y) = \left\{\!\! \begin{array}{lcl} \textsf{the $\frac{N+1}{2}$-th observation} & & \textsf{if $N$ is odd} \\ \textsf{the $\frac{N}{2}$-th observation} & & \textsf{if $N$ is even} \end{array}\right.}\]

\[\textsf{Quantiles: } \color{blue}{y_q \textsf{ on the data scale such that } \Pr(Y\leq y_{q})\geq q}\]

Measures of Spread (or dispersion)

\[ \textsf{Range: } \color{blue}{\max(Y)-\min(Y)}\]

\[\textsf{Interquartile range: IQR} = \color{blue}{y_U-y_L, \quad\textsf{where} \left\{\!\!\begin{array}{l} y_U: \Pr(Y\leq y_U)\geq 0.75 \\ y_L: \Pr(Y\leq y_L)\geq 0.25\end{array}\right.}\]

\[\displaystyle\textsf{Variance: } \color{blue}{\sigma^2=\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(y_i-\mu)^2}{N}}\]

NB: Standard deviation: \(\sigma=\sqrt{\sigma^2}\) is on the same scale as the data

Comparing multiple distributions

Comparing multiple distributions

  • When presenting data in the format shown in the previous graph, it is a good idea to use a meaningful ordering

    • For instance, in this case, bottom-left = poorer vs top-right = richer

  • This simple graph seems to indicate a relatively obvious divide between western countries and “the rest”

  • New Zealand and Australia constitute a group on their own among the richest

  • We may want to aggregate countries in larger groups to better visualise and summarise the outputs

    • West: Western and Southern Europe; North America; Australia & New Zealand
    • Sub-Saharan: Northern Africa; Sub-Saharan Africa
    • East Asia: Eastern Asia; South-Eastern Asia
    • Latin America: Caribbean; Central America; South America
    • Other: Other African countries

  • NB: This grouping is absolutely arbitrary and, while it has some reasonable geo-political rationale, is not an underlying “truth” (if anything ever is…)

Don’t always log…

Comparing multiple distributions

  • Re-scaling the data on the log has several advantages
    • “Stretches” the data, so differences are easier to spot
    • Makes data more symmetrical, so Normality more plausible (so can use simpler methods, eg linear regression)
    • Stabilises numerical computation (as values that are “too big” are scaled down)



  • BUT: sometimes we may be missing out on some important features in the natural scale
    • Direct interpratation of the values — with the natural scale we can see exactly what level of income we are talking about!
    • Can appreciate spread of variables — some “West” countries have incomes that are as low as many of the poorer areas; similarly, there are “outliers” in “East Asia” and “Latin America”, which are just as rich as the richest countries

Confounding

Don’t trust the data at face value…

  • We need to be careful to take summary/descriptive statistics or visualisation at face value!
  • There are many classical examples of “confounding” in many applications
    • “Effects” can be masked/modified by variables that we do not observe
    • Phenomena such as “Simpson’s Paradox”: exposure to a health condition is not bad for men and is not bed for women. But it’s bad when we observe the whole population



  • For example, suppose you observe the following data
Exposure Disease No disease Risk
Exposed 81 29 =81/(81+29)=0.7364
Not exposed 28 182 =28/(28+182)=0.1333

\[ \textsf{Relative risk} = \frac{0.7364}{0.1333}=5.52 \]


  • We might conclude that exposure to a certain risk factor increases highly the chances of getting a disease
  • In fact, exposed people are over 5 times more likely to get the disease

Confounding

Don’t trust the data at face value…

  • Now imagine that we can actually observe a third variable (eg sex)
Sex=Male
Sex=Female
Exposure Disease No disease Risk Disease No disease Risk
Exposed 1 9 0.1 80 20 0.8
Non exposed 20 180 0.1 8 2 0.8
Relative risk 1.0 1.0


  • If we “control” for sex, it appears that there is no effect at all (the relative risks are the same for exposed and non exposed in both groups)
  • How is that paradox possible?

Confounding

Don’t trust the data at face value…

  • The explanation of the paradox is in the fact that sex (the confounder) is associated with the risk factor
Sex=Male
Sex=Female
Exposure Disease No disease Risk Disease No disease Risk
Exposed 1 9 0.1 80 20 0.8
Non exposed 20 180 0.1 8 2 0.8
Relative risk 1.0 1.0

\[ \textsf{RR}_{\text{F}/\text{M}} = \frac{88/(88+22)}{21/(21+189)}=8 \]


  • The disease is 8 times more likely to occur in females than in males
  • But, in the sample:
    • The majority of exposed people are female (100 vs 10), who are at greater risk of getting the disease
    • The majority of not exposed are male (200 vs 10), who are a lower risk
  • This explains the paradox!

  • In all cases, the Pearson correlation between \(X\) and \(Y\) (measuring linear association between two variables) is vitually 0

    • BUT: no correlation can come from a random scatter of points, or any other pattern with no systematic trend (either up- or downwards)…
